m","justification":"This is fundamentally OS-level concurrency behavior. Real failures hide in lock contention, thread starvation, or blocking in shared code paths. An in-process mock of slow processing won't expose these—the mock runs in the same thread/event loop. Wall-clock timing under real concurrent OS load is the only way to detect hidden synchronous code or resource exhaustion. Unit and Integration tests with local mocks can pass even if the real code blocks under load.","test_description":"Spawn 10+ concurrent HTTP requests via test server or load tool. Send request #1 with downstream that sleeps 2+ seconds. Immediately send requests #2-10 with fast downstream. Measure actual response times for all requests. Verify p99 latency is <3 seconds, even while request #1 is slow.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"System-level concurrent load is the only reliable way to expose timing bugs and contention issues that mocks hide.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"An event whose ID was already received is not written to the queue a second time (deduplication)","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is deduplication logic (check seen IDs, skip if seen). Unit test of dedup logic alone could miss the persistent ID store interaction. Real failure comes from: (a) not actually storing/checking against the ID store, (b) race condition where two identical IDs arrive concurrently and both pass the check before either is stored. Integration with a real ID store (or in-process test double) and concurrent request simulation catches both.","test_description":"Send first request with event ID 'ev_abc_123', verify it's enqueued. Send a second request with the same ID. Verify the second request is rejected or silently dropped (ID not re-enqueued). Query queue and confirm only one copy of 'ev_abc_123' exists. Also test concurrent race: send two requests with the same ID in parallel; verify only one reaches the queue.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration with a persistent ID store and concurrent request execution catches both logic and race-condition failures.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"When the queue reports it is full, the handler returns 503 Service Unavailable with Retry-After header","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Handler logic: 'if queue reports full, return 503 with Retry-After.' Could be tested at Unit with a mocked queue that reports isFull()=true. But real failure might hide in: (a) handler doesn't check isFull(), (b) handler catches the exception but returns wrong status/headers, (c) queue reports full via exception, not a method. Integration test wiring handler with a queue that actually reports full (via mock or real library) catches all these.","test_description":"Configure queue mock to return true for queue.isFull(). Send a request. Verify response status is 503. Verify Retry-After header is present and contains a valid duration (e.g., 60 seconds).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration catches integration logic bugs; Unit could work but is riskier if the real queue's API differs from the mock.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"The persistent queue actually enforces its configured capacity limit and rejects events that would exceed it","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This tests the queue itself, not the handler. Real failure: queue accepts more than capacity. Can't test with a mocked queue that enforces capacity (that tests the mock, not the real behavior). Need a real queue library (in-process) or a realistic test double that actually implements capacity logic. If the persistent queue is an external message broker, System testing (against real Ka